. Note when the initial complaint was filed, what internal processes have been followed (such as HR investigations, grievance procedures, or mediation attempts), whether any external agencies are involved (EEOC, state labor boards, arbitration forums), the current stage of any formal proceedings, upcoming deadlines or hearings, and what procedural steps remain. This chronology enables readers to understand both what has occurred and what actions may be required going forward.\n\nIf any resolution has been reached, document its terms comprehensively. Include whether the matter was resolved through settlement, arbitration award, administrative decision, or other means. Specify any monetary compensation, non-monetary remedies such as reinstatement or policy changes, confidentiality provisions, non-admission clauses, and ongoing obligations for either party. Note whether the resolution is final or subject to appeal or further review.\n\nThroughout the summary, maintain strict objectivity and avoid legal conclusions unless they have been formally determined by a court, arbitrator, or administrative body. Use clear, professional language accessible to both legal and HR professionals. Identify any gaps in documentation or areas where additional investigation may be needed. Flag potential legal risks, including exposure to litigation, regulatory violations, or precedent-setting implications for company policy.\n\nStructure the summary to enable quick reference, with clear section headings and concise paragraphs. Begin with an executive overview that captures the essential nature of the dispute in two to three sentences. Include a parties section identifying all individuals and entities involved with their roles. Present the substantive sections on allegations, responses, procedure, and resolution in logical order. Conclude with a section on outstanding issues, next steps, and recommendations for HR or legal counsel consideration.\n\nEnsure all factual assertions are support